ions":["Cervical osteophytes","Oropharyngeal tumour","Parkinson disease","Pharyngeal pouch","Post-radiation fibrosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDysphagia can be categorised as oropharyngeal or oesophageal, and the causes can be either functional or structural.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes functional oropharyngeal dysphagia through impaired coordination of swallowing muscles. Other neurological causes include stroke and motor neurone disease.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EStructural causes include:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-radiation fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E from radiotherapy treatment\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E (Zenker diverticulum)\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOropharyngeal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E causing mechanical obstruction\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical osteophytes\u003C/strong\u003E causing external compression\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dysphagia can be categorised into oral, pharyngeal, and oesophageal causes","Neurological conditions affecting muscle control can cause functional oropharyngeal dysphagia","Structural causes of oropharyngeal dysphagia include post-radiation changes and tumours"],"references":["Panebianco M, Marchese-Ragona R, Masiero S, Restivo DA. Dysphagia in neurological diseases: a literature review. Neurol Sci. 2020 Nov;41(11):3067-3073. doi: 10.1007/s10072-020-04495-2. Epub 2020 Jun 7. PMID: 32506360; PMCID: PMC7567719","Wilkinson JM, Codipilly DC, Wilfahrt RP. Dysphagia: Evaluation and Collaborative Management. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Jan 15;103(2):97-106. PMID: 33448766","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroente